Testing the impact of volcanic eruption frequency on multidecadal temperature variability

Kira Rehfeld

28.02.2019

Reading in CMIP5/CMIP6 forcing data, translate it to effective radiative forcing, run 0D EBM with different combinations of forcing.

Earths global energy balance can be written as C dT/dt= (1-alpha)Q-sigmaepsilonT^4 where C [in units of J/(kg*K)] is the heat capacity of the system, set here to C=1.510^9J/(kgK), Q=S/4 is 1/4 of the solar constant, epsilon=0.6 is the emissivity, sigma is the boltzmann-constant and alpha the planetary albedo (0.3). The heat capacity C is that of a 1m^2 surface oceanic box, computed as frhoch, with f a scaling factor reflecting the oceanic fraction of the planet, rho the density of water, c the specific heat capacity of water and h a depth of the ocean box. For a fixed value of Q, the ODE solution describes the systems convergence to an equilibrium state. However, in a simplified experiment, volcanic perturbations can also be considered disturbances in the energy balance, modeled by a radiative forcing anomaly relative to the equilibrium state, Delta F. C dT/dt= (1-alpha)(Q+Delta F)-sigmaepsilonT^4

We obtain Delta F (all=CO2+solar+volcanic, volcanic) from the forcing reconstructions (REF? RAPHI?), translating AOD values to effective radiative forcing to W/m^2 (-25W/m^2 per 1 unit AOD), ref: AR5/AR6.

The EBM response under full/volcanic only forcing shows consistent multi-decadal variability between the two forcing scenarios (FIG ebm_results_volc_all_forcingH.pdf)

To further test the influence of volcanic forcing on multidecadal GMT variability, a stochastic volcanic forcing experiment is performed. For this, the 2000-year-long volcanic history is split in 133 segments which start from a near-zero volcanic background flux before an eruption, and which contain an event, as well as the subsequent decay to a background flux (-0.115W/m^2). For volcanic surrogates, we randomly draw from these 133 volcanic epochs to construct 2000-year long forcing histories. The EBM is run for 1000 randomized forcing histories. A considerable proportion of the resulting GMT variability is contained in the multidecadal frequency band (red dot at x=0 in Fig. multidec_ratio_volcforcing_h500_nmc_1000_28022019.pdf and inset). Now, keeping the overall forcing variability fixed to (var(Delta F)=0.6W/m^2+0.01), we decrease the recurrence time for volcanic eruptions by mixing in non-volcanic background epochs, adding Gaussian distributed noise over the whole time period (Fig. multidec inset b) such that with fewer eruptions white noise becomes stronger. We then evaluate the ratio of multidecadal (30-200a) variance to total variance using power spectra (c.f. Rehfeld et al. 2018). We find that with the increase of the recurrence time of volcanic events the relative proportion of variance in the multidecadal to centennial band decreases.

getresponse<-function(VolcH,Ftime,inttime,parms){
  tmp<-getebm.0d(Flux=cbind(Ftime,VolcH),inttime,interp="linear",parms=parms,plot=FALSE)
  out<-coredata(tmp$tsout)
  rm(tmp)
  return(out)
}
RV<-vector(mode = "list",length=length(FF))
ensresponse<-function(repzero,SP,inttime,Ftime,targetvarout,nmc=10){
  res<-list()
  FMat<-replicate(nmc,drawfrom(SP,max(inttime)+1,plot=FALSE,repzero=repzero,fixvarout = TRUE,targetvarout = targetvarout)$dR_Volc)
  #LS.f<-apply(FMat,2,function(x,tsc.in){tsc_dep_var(zoo(x,order.by=Ftime),tsc.in)},tsc.in=tsc.in)
  
  res$exmpl<-getebm.0d(Flux=cbind(Ftime,FMat[,1]),inttime,interp="linear",parms=parms,plot=FALSE)
  res$FORC.all<-apply(FMat,2,var)
  res$RMat<-apply(FMat,2,getresponse,Ftime=Ftime,inttime=inttime,parms=parms)
  LS<-res$LS<-apply(res$RMat,2,function(x,tsc.in){tsc_dep_var(zoo(x,order.by=Ftime),tsc.in)},tsc.in=tsc.in)
  #   # tot.var<-sapply(LS,function(x){x$var.tot})
  res$mdec.var<-sapply(LS,function(x){x$var.tsc})
  res$tot.var<-(apply(res$RMat,2,var)) # total variance
  res$RES.md<-res$mdec.var
  res$RES.all<-res$tot.var
  
  return(res)
}
